etymology:
Inherited from Ottoman Turkish قاتمق (katmak, “to add, join, mix, embroil”), from Proto-Turkic *kat- (“to mix, add, tie to”).
Cognates
Cognate with Old Uyghur [script needed] (kat-, “to mix, add”), Karakhanid [script needed] (katmāk, “to mix, add”), Azerbaijani qatmaq (“to add”), Bashkir ҡатыу (qatıw, “to mix up”), Chagatai [script needed] (qatmaq, “to mix, blend”), Chuvash хутӑш (hut̬ăš, “mixture”), Kazakh қату (qatu, “to fill, spice”), Khakas хадарға (xadarğa, “to admix”), Kipchak [Arabic needed] (kat-, “to join one thing to another”), Kyrgyz катуу (katuu, “to add”), Southern Altai кадар (kadar, “to add, twist”), Tatar кату (qatu, “to fill, bind, tie”), Turkmen gatmak (“to add, mix”), Tuvan каъдар (kàdar, “to add, twist”), Uyghur قاتماق (qatmaq, “to mix”), Yakut хат (qat, “to twist”).
